    "from utils_graph import compute_fidelity\n",
    "\n",
    "node_mask_ig = explanation_ig.node_mask.mean(dim=-1).cpu()\n",
    "\n",
    "base_score_ig, keep_score_ig, deletion_score_ig, important_nodes_ig = compute_fidelity(\n",
    "    explanation=explanation_ig,\n",
    "    model=model,\n",
    "    sub_x=sub_x,\n",
    "    sub_edge_index=sub_edge_index,\n",
    "    target_sub_idx=target_sub_idx,\n",
    "    threshold= 0,\n",
    "    device=device,\n",
    " )\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"\\n── Fidelity Integrated Gradients ───────────────────\")\n",
    "print(f\"  P(fraud) baseline           : {base_score_ig:.4f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"  P(fraud) keep test          : {keep_score_ig:.4f}  (Δ = {keep_score_ig - base_score_ig:+.4f})\")\n",
    "print(f\"  P(fraud) deletion test      : {deletion_score_ig:.4f}  (Δ = {deletion_score_ig - base_score_ig:+.4f})\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Nodes in explained subgraph : {len(important_nodes_ig)}\")\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "Q9XK-KnTFJvd"
   },
   "source": [
    "### 9.1 Edge-based Attribution\n",
    "\n",
    "In this setting, the edge weights are treated as differentiable inputs.  \n",
    "The baseline corresponds to a graph where all local edges have weight `0`, while the input corresponds to the original local subgraph where all edges have weight `1`.\n",
    "\n",
    "The attribution is computed with respect to the predicted probability of the fraud class.  \n",
    "Since Integrated Gradients can assign both positive and negative attributions, the absolute attribution values are used to rank the most influential edges regardless of direction of contribution.\n",
    "\n",
    "The final edge scores are normalized between `0` and `1` to make them easier to compare and visualize."
   ]
  },
