    "\n",
    "The learned node mask is quite broad: the mean node importance is high and almost all nodes receive a non-zero score.  \n",
    "This suggests that the explainer does not isolate only a very small subset of nodes, but instead identifies a wider structural neighborhood as relevant for preserving the fraud prediction.\n",
    "\n",
    "The target node is ranked first with an importance score of `1.0000`, as expected, because it was explicitly kept active and forced to maximum relevance after normalization.  \n",
    "The remaining top-ranked nodes include both legitimate and unknown-label nodes, showing that the explanation is not based only on fraud-labeled nodes, but also on the surrounding graph context.\n",
    "\n",
    "The derived edge ranking is very consistent with the structure observed in the previous explainers: all top-ranked edges point directly to the selected target node.  \n",
    "Since these edge scores are derived from node importance, they should be interpreted as a visualization and ranking aid rather than as directly learned edge-level causal scores.\n",
    "\n",
    "Overall, the CausGNN-style explanation suggests that the fraud prediction is supported by a broad set of incoming neighbors, with the target node and its immediate incoming connections playing the most central role."
   ]
  },
